article.headline: Blackmon becomes Bears' all-time shot blocker
article.linkText: Baylor polishes off Washington in second half
article.story:
SEATTLE (AP) -- It was a happy 21st birthday for Sophia Young,
who scored a season-high 22 points in sixth-ranked Baylor's 74-58
victory over Washington on Wednesday night.

Young made 11-of-15 from the field and helped the Lady Bears to
their eighth straight victory.

"She had a very good birthday," coach Kim Mulkey-Robertson
said. "A lot of good things happened out there tonight. The thing
about this team is that they're beginning to understand that
they're not too bad. We're a pretty good basketball team."

It definitely showed in the second half, as the Lady Bears ran
away from the Huskies. Washington was held to only one basket in
the final nine minutes.

Baylor (8-1) has not lost since a season-opening 1-point defeat
to top-ranked Louisiana State. The winning streak matches a run the
Lady Bears had during the 2002-03 campaign.

This game was close in the first half with Washington leading
the majority of the time. Cameo Hicks opened the second half with a
driving baseline layup that gave the Huskies a 44-42 lead on their
first possession. Baylor responded with a 10-0 run that included
back-to-back 3-pointers by Emily Niemann. It gave the Lady Bears a
lead they would never surrender.

"They did a lot better job on us defensively in the second
half," Washington's Kayla Burt said. "They were paying more
attention to their switches on the double screen, and we weren't
able to get open. When we did, we were off on the shot."

Steffanie Blackmon, Niemann and Chameka Scott had 15 points
apiece for Baylor. Blackmon added two blocked shots in the game,
making her Baylor's all-time leading shot blocker with 142.

Washington (4-5) played well in the first half, when it led by
as many as 11 points, but the shots didn't fall after the break.

"We came in ranked and we were on their home floor so we
expected to get their best shot early," Mulkey-Robertson said.
"It also didn't surprise me that we withstood their run. We've
been in that situation before. It's a sign of our maturity and our
getting better as a program."

Hicks led the Huskies with 15 points. Burt scored all 14 of hers
in the first half.

Washington, which has lost four of its last five games, took a
13-4 lead in the first four minutes. Baylor tied it at 38 apiece on
a layup by Blackmon.

The Huskies shot 34 percent for the game, and have not shot
better than 40 percent in any game this season.
